alfe-file-protocol — file-IPC driver for the CAD backends
=========================================================

See also: alfe.plan, alfe-backend-interface.issue,
alfe-backend-bricscad.issue, alfe-backend-autocad.issue,
spec sections "Protocole REPL distant", "Contrat AutoLISP côté
runtime".

Context
-------

AutoLISP inside BricsCAD or AutoCAD has no IPC mechanism beyond
files: no sockets, no pipes, no shared memory, and the REPL lives
inside the GUI. The historical bash wrapper therefore implements a
small file protocol with a CAD-side runtime
(`runtime/autolisp-remote-io.lsp`) and a shell-side driver
(`lib/autolisp-remote-io.sh`).

This issue rewrites the *driver* (the shell) in Common Lisp as
`alfe.protocol.file`. The CAD-side runtime (the .lsp) is reused
verbatim — it is AutoLISP code that runs inside the CAD engine, not
something the rewrite touches.

In scope
--------

  1. Session bring-up (`alfe.protocol.file:make-session WORKDIR`):
       - create `WORKDIR/protocol/` with the documented file slots
         (`status.txt`, `stdin.txt`, `stdout.txt`, `stderr.txt`,
         `control.txt`, `heartbeat.txt`, `read-buffer.lsp`,
         `runtime-info.txt`) ;
       - publish `BOOTING` to `status.txt` via the atomic-publish
         primitive ;
       - emit `run-common.lsp` populated with the spec's variables
         (`*AUTOLISP-*`, including the `*AUTOLISP-PROTOCOL-*`
         family) ;
       - resolve the AutoLISP runtime path
         (`autolisp-remote-io.lsp`) and stage it under
         `WORKDIR/runtime/` for the CAD to load.

  2. Atomic write primitive:
       - `(write-atomic-file PATH CONTENT)` writes to
         `PATH.tmp.<pid>.<rand>` then `rename-file` to PATH ;
       - used for every shell-to-runtime write (`stdin.txt`,
         `control.txt`) ;
       - the runtime side is *not* atomic when writing
         `stdout.txt`/`stderr.txt` — appending is the contract per
         the spec; alfe reads incrementally.

  3. Status polling:
       - `(wait-for-status PATH EXPECTED &key timeout)` and
         `(wait-for-status-prefix PATH PREFIX &key timeout)` poll
         with backoff (50 ms → 500 ms).
       - States from the spec's table are constants in
         `alfe.protocol.file:+status-*+` for type-safe matching.

  4. Line-to-form reader. Implement the AutoLISP `read`-over-lines
     contract described in the spec's "Modèle de lecture":
       - read whole lines until the accumulated text balances
         (parens, strings, comments — reuse
         `clautolisp.autolisp-reader:read-runtime-from-string` and
         catch the `:unexpected-eof` diagnostic to know when to
         accumulate another line) ;
       - present the balanced form to the consumer (`eval-plan`
         interactive loop).

  5. Output draining. `(drain-output SESSION)` advances offsets in
     `stdout.txt`/`stderr.txt` and returns the new text. Position
     tracking is per-channel inside the session struct.

  6. Control commands. `(send-control SESSION COMMAND)` atomic-
     publishes `PING` / `SHUTDOWN` / `INTERRUPT`. The runtime's
     consumption is destructive (file deleted after read); alfe
     re-publishes when the slot is free.

  7. Heartbeat. Optional `(read-heartbeat SESSION)` returns the last
     timestamp; alfe's `--verbose` may surface it. Treat absence as
     "no heartbeat published yet", not as failure.

  8. CAD-side runtime emission. A pure-CL emitter writes the
     `run-common.lsp` template documented in the spec, substituting
     the placeholders (`${LISP_OUTFILE}`, `${LISP_PROTOCOL_DIR}`,
     etc.) with workdir-resolved absolute paths. The template lives
     in source — *not* a separate file — to keep the runtime
     contract under version control.

  9. Tests under `tests/file-protocol-tests.lisp`:
       - atomic-write contention (parallel writers; verify atomic
         arrival semantics) ;
       - status wait reaches expected state and times out cleanly ;
       - drain-output handles partial lines (no torn UTF-8) ;
       - line-to-form reader composes the right AutoLISP form for
         the canonical multi-line test case ;
       - end-to-end against a *mock CAD* (a Lisp thread that
         emulates the CAD-side runtime against the same file slots).

Out of scope
------------

  - Per-CAD bring-up (binary discovery, AppleScript / COM bridges,
    template DWG resolution). Lives in alfe-backend-bricscad.issue
    and alfe-backend-autocad.issue.
  - Modifying `autolisp-remote-io.lsp` itself. The runtime is reused
    as-is; if the protocol grows, this issue's CL emitter learns to
    bundle the new revision.

Acceptance criteria
-------------------

  - The session bring-up function produces a `WORKDIR/protocol/`
    layout that matches the spec byte-for-byte (filenames,
    permissions, initial contents).
  - A mock CAD test scripts the full lifecycle (BOOTING → READY 0 →
    RUNNING 1 → DONE 1 OK → STOPPING → STOPPED) and asserts every
    transition.
  - All atomic-write tests pass without flake under load (run the
    suite 100× in CI; no race).
  - The line-to-form reader produces a balanced form for the test
    cases in the spec's "Cas d'usage visés".

Notes
-----

The hardest bug in this layer is racing publishers/consumers. Lean
on `clautolisp.autolisp-runtime`'s existing source-tracking
diagnostics to surface "partial read of stdin.txt" cleanly. The
runtime side already handles atomicity correctly; alfe must not
introduce a regression by writing non-atomically.
